<h2 id="what-the-template-includes">What the Template Includes</h2>
<p>Our website audit template is a structured workbook containing 72 checkpoints organised across seven tabs, each covering a distinct audit area. The template is designed to be used by SEO professionals, marketing managers, and web developers who need a systematic framework for evaluating website health without starting from scratch.</p>
<p><strong>Technical SEO tab (18 checkpoints).</strong> Covers crawlability, indexation, site architecture, server configuration, Core Web Vitals, mobile usability, HTTPS implementation, and structured data validation. Each checkpoint includes a description of what to check, the tool required to verify it, a pass/fail/partial status column, a notes column for documenting specific findings, and a priority rating to help with implementation planning.</p>
<p><strong>On-page SEO tab (14 checkpoints).</strong> Covers title tags, meta descriptions, heading structure, keyword targeting, URL optimisation, image alt text, internal linking, and Open Graph tags. The template includes formula-based conditional formatting that highlights failed checks in red and partial passes in amber, giving you an instant visual summary of on-page health.</p>
<p><strong>Content quality tab (12 checkpoints).</strong> Covers thin content identification, duplicate content detection, keyword cannibalisation, search intent alignment, content freshness, E-E-A-T signals, and orphan page discovery. This tab includes a content inventory section where you can log every indexed page with its word count, traffic, and quality assessment.</p>
<p><strong>Off-page SEO tab (8 checkpoints).</strong> Covers backlink profile health, toxic link identification, referring domain quality, link velocity, unlinked brand mentions, and social signal integration. The template includes columns for logging specific toxic links identified and tracking disavow file submissions.</p>
<p><strong>Local SEO tab (8 checkpoints).</strong> Covers Google Business Profile optimisation, NAP consistency, local schema markup, location page quality, review management, and local content assessment. This tab is optional for businesses without a local search component and can be hidden or deleted without affecting the rest of the workbook.</p>
<p><strong>UX and performance tab (7 checkpoints).</strong> Covers page speed metrics, mobile experience, navigation usability, form functionality, accessibility basics, and conversion path clarity. This tab bridges the gap between pure SEO checks and user experience evaluation.</p>
<p><strong>Summary dashboard.</strong> An auto-calculating summary tab that aggregates scores from all other tabs into an overall site health score, category scores, and a visual chart showing strengths and weaknesses at a glance. This dashboard is designed to be screenshot-ready for client presentations or stakeholder reports.</p>

<h2 id="how-to-use-it">How to Use It</h2>
<p>The template is most effective when used as part of a structured audit process rather than approached randomly. Follow this workflow for thorough, efficient auditing.</p>
<p><strong>Step 1: Gather your data first.</strong> Before opening the template, run the data collection that feeds into it. Crawl your site with Screaming Frog (free for up to 500 URLs). Export your Google Search Console performance data, coverage report, and Core Web Vitals report. Pull your backlink data from Ahrefs, SEMrush, or Majestic. Having this data ready before you start checking items prevents constant context-switching between tools and the template.</p>
<p><strong>Step 2: Work through tabs sequentially.</strong> Start with the Technical SEO tab because technical issues can invalidate the results of other checks. A page that is not indexed will fail every on-page and content check by default — fixing the indexation issue first may resolve cascading failures. After technical, move to on-page, then content, then off-page, and finally UX.</p>
<p><strong>Step 3: Record findings in detail.</strong> The notes column is not optional — it is where the real value lives. Instead of simply marking a check as "fail," document what specifically failed, which pages are affected, and what the fix requires. "Title tags — fail — 47 pages have duplicate titles, primarily product pages using the same template. Fix: Update product page template to generate unique titles from product name + category + brand." This specificity transforms the template from a checklist into an implementation brief.</p>
<p><strong>Step 4: Assign priority ratings.</strong> After completing all checks, review the failed items and assign priority ratings: P1 (critical, fix within 2 weeks), P2 (important, fix within 30 days), or P3 (beneficial, fix within 90 days). The priority should consider both the SEO impact and the effort required. A high-impact, low-effort fix is always P1 regardless of the category it sits in.</p>
<p><strong>Step 5: Review the summary dashboard.</strong> With all tabs completed, the summary dashboard auto-calculates your overall score and category scores. Use this as your executive overview for stakeholder communication and as your baseline for measuring improvement at the next audit.</p>

<h2 id="customisation-tips">Customisation Tips</h2>
<p>The template is designed as a starting point that you should adapt to your specific needs. No generic template perfectly fits every site, industry, or team workflow. Here are the most common and valuable customisations.</p>
<p><strong>Add industry-specific checks.</strong> E-commerce sites should add checks for product schema markup, faceted navigation handling, out-of-stock page management, and category page optimisation. SaaS sites should add checks for pricing page SEO, comparison page targeting, and documentation site optimisation. Publishers should add checks for news sitemap implementation, article schema, and content freshness signals. Add these as additional rows in the relevant tabs.</p>
<p><strong>Remove irrelevant sections.</strong> If your business has no local presence, hide or delete the Local SEO tab. If your site is a single-page application, some traditional technical checks may not apply — modify them to reflect JavaScript rendering-specific requirements instead. A leaner template that matches your actual needs is more useful than a comprehensive one full of "not applicable" entries.</p>
<p><strong>Add a client or project identifier.</strong> If you audit multiple sites (for clients or across a portfolio), add a header row with the site URL, client name, audit date, and auditor name. This makes archived templates identifiable when you need to reference previous audits for comparison.</p>
<p><strong>Create a "before and after" structure.</strong> Duplicate the status columns to create a "previous audit" and "current audit" comparison within the same template. This instantly shows which issues have been resolved since the last audit and which persist, making progress reporting effortless.</p>
<p><strong>Integrate with project management.</strong> Add columns for "assigned to," "due date," and "completion status" to transform the template from an audit tool into a project tracker. Some teams export failed checks directly into Jira, Asana, or Trello — the notes column provides enough detail for task descriptions when written thoroughly.</p>
<p><strong>Adjust the scoring weights.</strong> The default scoring weights the summary dashboard equally across categories. If technical SEO is a bigger concern for your site than content quality (or vice versa), adjust the weighting formula to reflect your priorities. This produces a site health score that more accurately reflects your specific situation.</p>

<h2 id="scoring-guide">Scoring Guide</h2>
<p>The template uses a three-tier scoring system for individual checks and a percentage-based scoring system for category and overall scores. Understanding the scoring logic helps you interpret results accurately and communicate them to stakeholders.</p>
<p><strong>Individual check scoring:</strong> Each checkpoint is scored as Pass (2 points), Partial (1 point), or Fail (0 points). Pass means the check is fully satisfied with no issues found. Partial means the check is satisfied for some pages or elements but not all — for example, 80% of pages have unique title tags but 20% share duplicates. Fail means the check is not satisfied or reveals a significant problem.</p>
<p><strong>Category scoring:</strong> Each tab's score is calculated as the percentage of total possible points achieved. A Technical SEO tab with 18 checks has a maximum score of 36 points (18 x 2). If you score 28/36, your technical SEO rating is 78%. The template automatically calculates and displays this percentage with conditional colour coding: green for 80%+, amber for 60-79%, red for below 60%.</p>
<p><strong>Overall site health score:</strong> The summary dashboard combines all category scores into a single 0-100 score using weighted averaging. The default weights are: Technical SEO 30%, On-page SEO 20%, Content Quality 20%, Off-page SEO 15%, UX/Performance 10%, Local SEO 5%. Adjust these weights based on your site's priorities.</p>
<p><strong>Interpreting scores:</strong> A score of 85-100 indicates a well-optimised site with minor improvements available. A score of 70-84 indicates a solid foundation with specific areas needing attention. A score of 50-69 indicates significant issues across multiple areas that are likely suppressing search performance. A score below 50 indicates fundamental problems that require urgent, systematic remediation.</p>
<p><strong>Score limitations:</strong> Numeric scores are useful for tracking progress and communicating simply, but they cannot capture the full picture. A site could score 75% overall while having a single critical technical issue (like a noindex tag on the homepage) that makes the score meaningless until resolved. Always review individual findings alongside aggregate scores. The score tells you how you are doing overall; the individual checks tell you what to fix.</p>
<p>When presenting scores to clients or stakeholders, always pair the number with context. "Your site scores 68%, which is below the average we see for sites in your industry (typically 72-78%). The main factors are page speed and content depth, both of which have clear remediation paths" is far more useful than just stating the score.</p>

<h2 id="when-to-re-audit">When to Re-Audit</h2>
<p>A single audit provides a snapshot. Regular re-auditing transforms that snapshot into a performance trajectory that validates your SEO investment and catches new issues before they cause damage.</p>
<p><strong>Quarterly full audits</strong> are the recommended cadence for sites where organic search is a significant revenue channel. Every three months, work through the complete template to assess overall health, measure improvement from implemented fixes, and identify new issues that have emerged. Quarterly auditing aligns well with typical business reporting cycles and provides enough time between audits for implemented changes to produce measurable results.</p>
<p><strong>Monthly technical checks</strong> are advisable for sites that update frequently. If you publish new content weekly, make regular template changes, or run frequent promotions that add and remove pages, a monthly scan of the Technical SEO tab catches new crawl errors, broken links, and indexation issues before they accumulate. This does not require a full audit — a focused technical review using an automated crawl tool takes one to two hours.</p>
<p><strong>Post-change audits</strong> should follow any significant site modification. After a CMS update, redesign, migration, plugin change, or structural navigation update, run at minimum the Technical SEO tab to verify nothing was broken. Migrations in particular warrant a full audit within two weeks of launch to catch redirect failures, lost meta data, and new technical issues.</p>
<p><strong>Post-algorithm update audits</strong> are warranted when Google confirms a major algorithm update and your traffic is affected. A focused audit of the areas the update targets (content quality for helpful content updates, link profile for spam updates, technical performance for page experience updates) helps diagnose whether the impact was caused by your site's deficiencies or broader algorithmic shifts.</p>
<p><strong>Annual comprehensive audits</strong> complement quarterly reviews by providing deeper analysis. Once per year, extend your audit to include competitive benchmarking, backlink profile deep-dive, content strategy review, and conversion path analysis. This annual review sets the strategic direction for the coming year, while quarterly audits maintain tactical execution.</p>
<p>Store completed templates in a shared location with clear date labelling. The ability to compare your current audit against the previous quarter's results is one of the template's most valuable features — it shows exactly how your site's health has changed over time and whether your SEO investment is producing measurable improvement.</p>

